Comprehensive US drug market analysis (IQVIA Rx). The latest weekly Total Prescription YoY growth (wk ending 8/22) was \(+2.3\%\) vs. \(+2.6\%\) last wk and \(+2.7\%\) over the past 12 wks.

For week ended Aug 22, US total market weekly TRx YoY change was \(+2.3\%\) vs. \(+0.8\%\) year ago (Exhibit7). Rolling 4- week TRx YoY was \(+2.6\%\) and rolling 12- week TRx YoY was \(+2.7\%\) . Extended unit (EUTRx) weekly YoY growth was \(+1.8\%\) , below TRx YoY (Exhibit 11). Sequential weekly TRx growth was \(+0.3\%\) compared to \(+1.1\%\) week before. Exhibit16- Exhibit18 depict YoY momentum for key products.

BMY's Cobenfy was approved for schizophrenia on 9/26/24. Scripts are \(\sim 2,160\) for the week vs \(\sim 2,100\) last week. For full details on our views on the launch see our note "Contextualizing Cobenfy launch expectations", where we discuss that the analogs we are most focused on are the schizophrenia volumes from the Rexulti, Caplyta, and Lybalvi launches. We estimated that to achieve 2025 consensus expectations Cobenfy TRx needs to track at \(\sim 2 - 3x\) the volumes from those launches (see Exhibit 1) based on the implied consensus trend as '25 estimates have declined to \(\) 17\(1mn from\) \ \(196m\) since our initial note, which implies \(\sim 129K\) TRx are required to reach consensus estimates (assuming a \(\sim\) 1,200 net price, in line with our estimated price in our BMY model). We also show the Cobenfy launch to date and our estimate of the trajectory to achieve consensus relative to recent anti- psychotic launches, with TRx combined across all indications, in Exhibit 2 below for reference as well.

VRTX's Journavex was approved for acute pain on 1/30/25. Scripts are \(\sim 7,060\) for the week vs \(\sim 6,890\) last week. VRTX notes that hospital scripts are not captured by IQVIA, which makes up \(\sim 35\%\) of total scripts, and it further confirms that the average script duration is \(^{14}\) days (LINK). We note VA cons estimate for 2025 has increased to \(\) 78\(mn from\) \ \(65mn\) after 2Q earnings. To achieve \(\) 78\(mn sales, we estimate that \(\sim 349\) total scripts are needed for 14 - day script duration (assuming\) \ \(225\) net price per script, where we assume \(50\%\) GTN, but note we have limited visibility). Baged on 2Q Journavex sales and scripts, we estimate the GTN to be \(\sim 69\%\) Using a line method, we project the weekly TRx needed to achieve cons estimate, by flexing the GTN from \(50\% - 75\%\) for 14- day scripts (Exhibit 3). In addition, we include a line where the actual scripts are grossed up with estimated hospital scripts, such that \(35\%\) of the total scripts come from hospitals.

The IQVIA databases are different for prescription (Rx) and sales (\$), and the IQVIA sales dollars only reflect list prices of drugs and not rebates/discounts. TRx represents total prescription dispensed including refills. NRx represents new prescriptions — that is, all scripts written except refills. However, the NRx also includes renewals—the script patients get when they run out of refills.

Remicade biosimilar PFE's Inflectra adoption has decreased in recent months. OGN's Renflexis is slow to be adopted. PFE's Inflectra has been on the market for \(>3\) years (launched in mid Dec- 16). MRK's Renflexis, launched in late July- 17, started to appear in IQVIA from September, 2017 only. We believe payers are choosing not to support the biosimilar because the pricing is not low enough below the net pricing of branded Remicade and because they would lose branded rebates on existing Remicade patients who remain on the brand. AMGN's A vsola was approved on Dec. 6, 2019 and launched in July 2020. Pfizer has decided not to launch ixifi in the US.

NRx represents new prescriptions including renewals and excluding refills, so it does not represent new patient starts. Renewals are the scripts patients get to continue the drug when they run out of refills.

EUTRx / EUNRx (Extended Units) figures can represent a more accurate picture of demand because they include weighting of larger/longer duration Rx. Standard NRx / TRx / NRx count both a 30- day and a 90- day prescription the same. Counts include dispensed tablets, capsules, milliliters, and so forth. NPA: "National estimates of prescriptions, or the rate at which drugs move out of the pharmacy and into the hands of a consumer via formal dispensed prescriptions".
NSP: "National sales estimates of product packages into retail drugstores, hospitals, clinics, and other nonretail type outlets".
NSP units: "Total amount of packages sold of a particular drug to the dispensing outlet/ chain/hospital."

NSP Price: "Is based on a number of sources, depending upon Class of Trade (Channel). It generally represents a best estimation of Net price without the impact of proprietary rebating by the manufacturer. Equation = Sales \(\Phi\) / Units".
NSP Sales \(\Phi\) : "Total amount of the sales into the dispensing outlets, chain, and health care providers from the manufacturers and distribution centers expressed in US dollars."

IQVIA sales data (NSP) is captured weekly, and grouped into 4 or 5 week 'months.' The weeks start in January, so the 5 week month falls at the end of each quarter: March, June, September, and December. Periodically, an extra week is added in November to ensure that DDD reporting months do not deviate too far from calendar months.

Brief from IQVIA on NSP Price: Note that NSP reflects significant Class Of Trade discounts and is often well below Gross Price even though it does not reflect rebates manufacturers pay to payers. "Our NSP Sales \(\Phi\) 's represent a trade price or transaction price. It is the actual cost that was charged to acquire the pharmaceutical products as seen on the purchase invoice. NSP is a projected database. What that means is IQVIA collects the data from the sample (which for NSP represents about \(88\%\) ) and using IQVIA methodology, the data is projected to \(100\%\) of the universe. The prices reflected in IQVIA National Sales Perspectives" are the prices outlets (i.e. pharmacies, hospitals, clinics) pay for the products, whether purchased directly from a manufacturer or indirectly via a wholesaler or chain warehouse. Invoice line item discounts are included. Prompt- payment discounts and bottom- line invoice discounts are not included. Rebates, typically paid by the manufacturer directly to a customer, insurer, or PBM (Pharmacy Benefits Manager), are not reflected."
